Theme 1: Matrix Determinants¶

1a. Implement a function called my_det that calculates the determinant of a matrix recursively using expansion by cofactors (i.e., the way you learned to compute them by hand in Math 18/Math 20F. This is the first method described here). The Matrix methods delete_columns and delete_rows may come in handy. You can assume the input is a square matrix.

In [16]:
def minor(M,i):
    minor = M.delete_rows([0])
    minor = minor.delete_columns([i])
    return minor

def my_det(M):
    if M.nrows() == 1:
        return M[0,0]
    else:
        determinant = 0
        for x in list(range(M.nrows())):
            determinant += M[0,x]*(-1)**(x+2)*det(minor(M,x))
        return determinant

Theme 2: Graphs and number theory¶

2a. Read the definition of a Paley graph, then write a function that, given a prime $p$ congruent to 1 modulo 4, constructs the Paley graph associated to that prime. (There also exist Paley graphs associated to prime powers, but your function need not construct those.) Note: Sage has a built-in function to do this: graphs.PaleyGraph(p). Your function should not use this one, but it gives a good way to check your work. (Hint: You may want to reread the section on quadratic residues in the lecture on 11-07-18.)

In [20]:
# this constructs a Paley graph
def my_paley(p):
    # raise an error message for an invalid input
    if mod(p,4) != 1:
        raise ValueError('p needs to be congruent to 1 modulo 4')
    else:
        edges = []
        v = [i for i in range(p)]
        qr = quadratic_residues(p)
        for i in range(p-1):
            for j in range(i+1,p):
                if (abs(v[i]-v[j]) in qr) and (set([v[i],v[j]]) not in edges):
                    edges.append(set([v[i],v[j]]))
        edges = list(map(tuple, edges))
        return Graph(edges)

In [22]:
# this produces Jacobsthal matrix which is used in Hadamard matrix
def Jacobsthal(p):
    # raise an error message for an invalid input
    if (mod(p,4) != 1) and (mod(p,4) != 3):
        raise ValueError('p needs to be congruent to 3 modulo 4')
    else:
        pos_1, neg_1, zeros = ([] for i in range(3))
        v = [i for i in range(p)]
        qr = quadratic_residues(p)
        for col in range(p):
            for row in range(p):
                if v[row]-v[col] == 0:
                    zeros.append(tuple([v[row],v[col]]))
                elif ((v[row]-v[col]) in qr) or ((p+(v[row]-v[col])) in qr):
                    pos_1.append(tuple([v[row],v[col]]))
                else:
                    neg_1.append(tuple([v[row],v[col]]))
        entries = []
        for i in range(p):
            for j in range(p):
                if (i,j) in pos_1:
                    entries.append(1)
                elif (i,j) in neg_1:
                    entries.append(-1)
                elif (i,j) in zeros:
                    entries.append(0)
        
        return entries

# this produces a Hadamard matrix
def Hadamard(p):
    # raise an error message for an invalid input
    if mod(p,4) != 1:
        raise ValueError('p needs to be congruent to 3 modulo 4')
    else:
        # construct [0, jT, j, Q]
        entries = [0]+[1 for _ in range(p)]
        j = Jacobsthal(p)
        for i in range(p):
            entries = entries + [1] + j[p*i:p*i+p]
        # Paley construction II
        final_entries = []
        for i in range(p+1):
            fr = []
            sr = []
            for j in range(p+1):
                if entries[i*p+j] == 0:
                    fr = fr + [1,-1]
                    sr = sr + [-1,-1]
                elif entries[i*p+j] == 1:
                    fr = fr + [1,1]
                    sr = sr + [1,-1]
                elif entries[i*p+j] == -1:
                    fr = fr + [-1,-1]
                    sr = sr + [-1,1]
            final_entries = final_entries + fr + sr
        
        return Matrix(2*(p+1),2*(p+1),final_entries)

2c. Check that your answer to 2b actually does achieve the Hadamard bound. According to Wikipedia, the Hadamard bound is the following

$$|det(N)|\leq\prod ||v_{i}||$$


So, we will apply this to our matrix.

In [26]:
# this tells if a Hadamard matrix achieve the Hadamard bound
def Hadamard_bound(p):
    H = Hadamard(p)
    norm = 1
    for i in range(2*(p+1)):
        norm *= H[:,i].norm()
    print('|det(N)| = ' + str(abs(det(H))))
    print('Norm = ' + str(norm))
    if abs(det(H)) <= norm:
        return True
    else:
        return false

Theme 4: Minimum spanning trees¶

William Stein announces the formation of CoCalc Fiber, a new broadband network which will connect the capital cities of the 48 continental United States (excluding Alaska and Hawaii) with a series of underground cables joining certain pairs of cities. Naturally, William wants to minimize the cost of building this network; he assumes that the cost of building a network link between some pairs of cities is proportional to the distance between those two cities.

4a. Define a function that implements the haversine formula: given two latitude-longitude pairs, compute the distance between those two points on Earth. Use kilometers instead of miles, because the US was supposed to convert to the metric system in 1975. Check your formula by computing the distance between Boston and San Diego, as reported by the Great Circle Mapper web site.

In [1]:
def haversine(loc_1, loc_2):
    # the earth radius
    r = 6378.1
    lon_dif = (loc_2[1] - loc_1[1])*pi/180
    lat_dif = (loc_2[0] - loc_1[0])*pi/180
    d = 2*r*arcsin(sqrt(sin((lat_dif)/2)**2 + cos(loc_1[0]*pi/180)*cos(loc_2[0]*pi/180)*sin((lon_dif)/2)**2))
    return RR(d)
In [2]:
san = [32.733556, -117.189666]
bos = [42.362944, -71.006388]
haversine(bos, san)
Out[2]:
4160.40556759925

The Great Circle Mapper web site shows that the distance between the two location $4164$ km. The difference is caused by the earth's radius. I used radius information from here. However, different websites says different radius. For example, this site says the earth's radii differ depending on the locations on the earth. So we can say that our function produced approximate value which is close enought to the actual distance.

5a. Write a Python function that takes as input a positive integer $k$ and the arrays $U$, $\Sigma$, and $V$. It should make a $768\times k$ matrix $U_k$ from the first $k$ columns of $U$, a $k\times k$ diagonal matrix $\Sigma_k$ with the first $k$ entries of $\Sigma$ along the diagonal, and a $k\times 1024$ matrix $V_k$ from the first $k$ rows of $V$. It should then multiply these matrices to get an approximation $U_k \Sigma_k V_k$ of the original matrix and plot the corresponding grayscale picture. Note that this product will give a $768\times 1024$ matrix, so it will be the correct size.

In [9]:
# this makes Sigma to Sigma_k
def diagonal_m(k, array):
    l = []
    for i in range(k-1):
        l.append(array[i])
        for _ in range(k):
            l.append(0)
    l.append(array[k-1])
    return Matrix(k,k,l)
In [10]:
def usv(k,U,Sigma,V):
    Uk, Sigmak, Vk = Matrix(U)[:,:k], diagonal_m(k,Sigma), Matrix(V)[:k,:]
    return plt.imshow(Uk*Sigmak*Vk, cmap=plt.cm.gray)

We tried three different $k$ values, $k=13,17,30,40$. When I showed the picture with $k=10$ to my friends, some of my friends told me the picture is a wolf rather than a racoon while all of my friends told me it is a racoon when I showed a picture with $k=17$. So, I conclude the smallest value for which the picture is recognizably a raccoon is $10$.
And I conclude the smallest value for which the picture is indistinguishable from the original is somewhere between $48$ and $55$ since the picture with $k=48$ looks a little pixeled around its eyes or fur. On the other hand, I think the picture with $k=55$ is indistinguishable unless you look at the picture very carefully (I could not determine the exact point since they are so similar).

5c. As a function of $k$, what is the total combined size (number of entries) of the parts of $U$, $\Sigma$, and $V$ that are used to reconstruct the original picture? What is the compression ratio for the two values you found in 5b? (I.e., what percent of the original data was used in the reconstruction?)

Because we use the first $k$ columns of $U$(each column has 768 data), the first $k$ elements of $\Sigma$, and the first $k$ rows of $V$(each row has 1024 data), the total combined size (number of entries) of the parts of $U$, $\Sigma$, and $V$ is
$$768k+k+1024k=1793k$$

The original size is $1793*768=1,377,024$
For $k=13$, the total combined size is $1793*10=17,930$. So, the compression ratio is $\frac{17,930}{1,377,024}=0.0130$

For $k=48$, the total combined size is $1793*48=86,064$. So, the compression ratio is $\frac{86,064}{1,377,024}=0.0625$
